So the mass of a fermion

1398
00:56:49,714 --> 00:56:51,214
is the mass of a particle.

1399
00:56:51,214 --> 00:56:53,214
It's not the mass of a particle that's broken,

1400
00:56:53,214 --> 00:56:56,214
but only if the symmetry is spontaneously broken.

1401
00:56:56,214 --> 00:56:59,214
So the Higgs phenomena has another role.

1402
00:56:59,214 --> 00:57:02,214
It gives the fermion's mass.

1403
00:57:02,214 --> 00:57:05,214
How big is the mass of the fermions?

1404
00:57:05,214 --> 00:57:09,214
The mass of a fermion is

1405
00:57:09,214 --> 00:57:13,214
equal to some G times F.

1406
00:57:13,214 --> 00:57:16,214
Now, there are different fermions in our world.

1407
00:57:16,214 --> 00:57:19,214
That only means that there are a collection

1408
00:57:19,214 --> 00:57:22,214
of different Gs in the world.

1409
00:57:22,214 --> 00:57:25,214
These Gs are called Yukawa couplings,

1410
00:57:25,214 --> 00:57:27,214
and there's one for each kind of fermion.

1411
00:57:27,214 --> 00:57:30,214
There's an electron Yukawa coupling.

1412
00:57:30,214 --> 00:57:32,214
Let's estimate.

1413
00:57:32,214 --> 00:57:34,214
How big is the electron Yukawa coupling?

1414
00:57:34,214 --> 00:57:36,214
Remember that the mass of the Z boson,

1415
00:57:36,214 --> 00:57:40,214
or the W boson, is essentially F.

1416
00:57:40,214 --> 00:57:43,214
Anybody know what the mass of a W boson is?

1417
00:57:43,214 --> 00:57:45,214
It's about 90.

1418
00:57:45,214 --> 00:57:47,214
It's about 900 GeV, right?

1419
00:57:47,214 --> 00:57:49,214
Did somebody say?

1420
00:57:49,214 --> 00:57:50,214
How much?

1421
00:57:50,214 --> 00:57:52,214
Sorry, 90 GeV, not 900.

1422
00:57:52,214 --> 00:57:53,214
Thank you.

1423
00:57:53,214 --> 00:57:56,214
Roughly 100 GeV.

1424
00:57:56,214 --> 00:57:58,214
What's the mass of an electron?

1425
00:57:58,214 --> 00:58:01,214
So we could be talking about electrons here.

1426
00:58:01,214 --> 00:58:05,214
This would be the Yukawa coupling for the electron.

1427
00:58:05,214 --> 00:58:07,214
Half an MeV, right?

1428
00:58:07,214 --> 00:58:14,214
So G electron here must be a very small number.

1429
00:58:14,214 --> 00:58:16,214
What is it?

1430
00:58:16,214 --> 00:58:18,714
It's the ratio of the

1431
00:58:18,714 --> 00:58:21,214
electron mass to the Z mass,

1432
00:58:21,214 --> 00:58:24,214
and that's 100 GeV versus half an MeV.

1433
00:58:24,214 --> 00:58:27,214
That's a big number.

1434
00:58:27,214 --> 00:58:28,214
Hundreds of thousands.

1435
00:58:28,214 --> 00:58:29,214
How much?

1436
00:58:29,214 --> 00:58:31,214
200 what?

1437
00:58:31,214 --> 00:58:40,214
That's 100 GeV versus half an MeV.

1438
00:58:40,214 --> 00:58:42,214
The difference between an MeV and a GeV

1439
00:58:42,214 --> 00:58:43,214
is a factor of 1,000,

1440
00:58:43,214 --> 00:58:45,214
so it's roughly a factor of 10 to...

1441
00:58:45,214 --> 00:58:49,214
This number is about 10 to the minus 5.

1442
00:58:49,214 --> 00:58:51,214
Very, very small number.

1443
00:58:51,214 --> 00:58:53,214
How do we know it?

1444
00:58:53,214 --> 00:58:54,714
We know it from knowing both

1445
00:58:54,714 --> 00:58:56,214
the mass of the W boson

1446
00:58:56,214 --> 00:58:58,214
and the mass of the electron.

1447
00:58:58,214 --> 00:59:00,214
Next.

1448
00:59:00,214 --> 00:59:01,214
What's the next one?

1449
00:59:01,214 --> 00:59:03,214
The next one is the muon, or the up quark,

1450
00:59:03,214 --> 00:59:05,214
or the down quark,

1451
00:59:05,214 --> 00:59:07,214
and there's a variety of different numbers.

1452
00:59:07,214 --> 00:59:10,214
What's the heaviest of the quarks?

1453
00:59:10,214 --> 00:59:11,214
The top quark.

1454
00:59:11,214 --> 00:59:12,214
The top quark, and what is that?

1455
00:59:12,214 --> 00:59:15,214
How much, what's its mass?

1456
00:59:15,214 --> 00:59:18,214
It's about a factor of 1 1⁄2 or 2 times,

1457
00:59:18,214 --> 00:59:21,214
somewhere between 1 1⁄2 and 2 times

1458
00:59:21,214 --> 00:59:24,214
the mass of the W.

1459
00:59:24,214 --> 00:59:27,214
So that means for the top quark,

1460
00:59:27,214 --> 00:59:30,214
this number here

1461
00:59:30,214 --> 00:59:34,214
is a number of order one.

1462
00:59:34,214 --> 00:59:36,214
So there's a whole spectrum

1463
00:59:36,214 --> 00:59:38,214
of these different Yukawa couplings

1464
00:59:38,214 --> 00:59:41,214
that nobody understands.

1465
00:59:41,214 --> 00:59:44,214
But one thing that's interesting is you,

1466
00:59:44,214 --> 00:59:46,214
and you say, so, okay, so all you've done

1467
00:59:46,214 --> 00:59:51,214
is fit a collection of numbers

1468
00:59:51,214 --> 00:59:53,214
to the masses of the fermions.

1469
00:59:53,214 --> 00:59:56,214
But now you can hope for an experimental

1470
00:59:56,214 --> 01:00:00,214
conservation, experimental confirmation

1471
01:00:00,214 --> 01:00:02,214
of these numbers.

1472
01:00:02,214 --> 01:00:06,214
Let's go back to the coupling

1473
01:00:06,214 --> 01:00:10,214
of the right-handed and the left-handed particles here.

1474
01:00:10,214 --> 01:00:13,214
And remember that F was simply

1475
01:00:13,214 --> 01:00:17,214
the frozen value of the Higgs field.

1476
01:00:17,214 --> 01:00:20,214
But the Higgs field is not really frozen.

1477
01:00:20,214 --> 01:00:23,214
It really can shift around.

1478
01:00:23,214 --> 01:00:25,214
What is the Higgs field?

1479
01:00:25,214 --> 01:00:27,214
The Higgs field is the fluctuation

1480
01:00:27,214 --> 01:00:29,214
away from this frozen value,

1481
01:00:29,214 --> 01:00:31,214
the real Higgs particle.

1482
01:00:31,214 --> 01:00:33,214
The real Higgs particle is the fluctuation

1483
01:00:33,214 --> 01:00:35,214
away from here.

1484
01:00:35,214 --> 01:00:37,214
So in fact, what we should really write,

1485
01:00:37,214 --> 01:00:39,214
if we're doing it correctly,

1486
01:00:39,214 --> 01:00:44,214
is F plus the Higgs field

1487
01:00:44,214 --> 01:00:48,214
times psi left.

1488
01:00:48,214 --> 01:00:50,214
What is this telling us?

1489
01:00:50,214 --> 01:00:52,214
This is telling us that, sorry,

1490
01:00:52,214 --> 01:00:54,214
this is right, this is right, I think.

1491
01:00:54,214 --> 01:00:56,214
No, left, yeah, left.

1492
01:00:56,214 --> 01:00:58,214
This is telling us that a process

1493
01:00:58,214 --> 01:01:02,214
can happen where a right-handed fermion

1494
01:01:02,214 --> 01:01:05,214
can turn into a left-handed fermion

1495
01:01:05,214 --> 01:01:08,214
and a Higgs particle, a real process.

1496
01:01:09,214 --> 01:01:11,214
Right-handed particle can become

1497
01:01:11,214 --> 01:01:14,214
a left-handed particle and a Higgs particle.

1498
01:01:14,214 --> 01:01:16,214
And what's the amplitude for that?

1499
01:01:16,214 --> 01:01:18,214
The same Yukawa coupling.

1500
01:01:18,214 --> 01:01:20,214
What is that word before coupling?

1501
01:01:20,214 --> 01:01:22,214
Yukawa.

1502
01:01:22,214 --> 01:01:24,214
Yukawa was a Japanese physicist.

1503
01:01:24,214 --> 01:01:27,214
Sorry. Yukawa.

1504
01:01:27,214 --> 01:01:32,214
Yukawa.

1505
01:01:32,214 --> 01:01:35,214
Yukawa was a Japanese physicist

1506
01:01:35,214 --> 01:01:38,214
in the 40s who,

1507
01:01:38,214 --> 01:01:42,214
among other things,

1508
01:01:42,214 --> 01:01:44,214
wrote down the mathematics

1509
01:01:44,214 --> 01:01:47,214
of the couplings between fermions

1510
01:01:47,214 --> 01:01:49,214
and bosons like this.

1511
01:01:49,214 --> 01:01:52,214
All right.

1512
01:01:52,214 --> 01:01:56,214
Won the Nobel Prize for this in the 1940s

1513
01:01:56,214 --> 01:01:58,214
for different physics,

1514
01:01:58,214 --> 01:02:00,214
for nuclear physics applications

1515
01:02:00,214 --> 01:02:02,214
of these ideas.

1516
01:02:02,214 --> 01:02:04,214
But in any case, the point is

1517
01:02:04,214 --> 01:02:07,214
that the same coupling constant

1518
01:02:07,214 --> 01:02:11,214
which appears in the mass of the fermions

1519
01:02:11,214 --> 01:02:14,214
also governs the process of a fermion

1520
01:02:14,214 --> 01:02:18,214
becoming a Higgs boson and another fermion.

1521
01:02:18,214 --> 01:02:21,214
I should draw these as solid lines.

1522
01:02:21,214 --> 01:02:24,214
Fermion left-handed becomes fermion right-handed

1523
01:02:24,214 --> 01:02:26,214
and a Higgs boson.

1524
01:02:26,214 --> 01:02:29,214
Now, we've not detected the Higgs bosons yet.

1525
01:02:29,214 --> 01:02:31,214
We've not detected them yet.

1526
01:02:31,214 --> 01:02:33,214
So it becomes a very, very important thing

1527
01:02:33,214 --> 01:02:35,214
once the Higgs boson is detected

1528
01:02:35,214 --> 01:02:37,214
to study the different processes

1529
01:02:37,214 --> 01:02:39,214
in which Higgs bosons are produced

1530
01:02:39,214 --> 01:02:42,214
to see that the relative probabilities

1531
01:02:42,214 --> 01:02:45,214
of producing a Higgs boson by an electron

1532
01:02:45,214 --> 01:02:48,214
and by a top quark or another kind of quark,

1533
01:02:48,214 --> 01:02:51,214
that they have the same ratios

1534
01:02:51,214 --> 01:02:54,214
as these constants here.

1535
01:02:54,214 --> 01:02:56,214
For example, it tells us

1536
01:02:56,214 --> 01:02:58,214
that in the decay of the Higgs boson,

1537
01:02:58,214 --> 01:02:59,714
this could be read as

1538
01:02:59,714 --> 01:03:01,214
the decay of a Higgs boson

1539
01:03:01,214 --> 01:03:03,214
into a pair of fermions,

1540
01:03:03,214 --> 01:03:05,214
that it prefers to have a fermion

1541
01:03:05,214 --> 01:03:09,214
that is supposed to decay into the heaviest fermions

1542
01:03:09,214 --> 01:03:12,214
if it has enough energy to do so.

1543
01:03:12,214 --> 01:03:15,214
It will preferentially decay to heavier fermions

1544
01:03:15,214 --> 01:03:17,214
rather than light fermions,

1545
01:03:17,214 --> 01:03:19,214
and that's a consequence of this

1546
01:03:19,214 --> 01:03:23,214
because the couplings here are larger.

1547
01:03:23,214 --> 01:03:26,214
So that's one of the things that will become important

1548
01:03:26,214 --> 01:03:28,214
in the LHC,

1549
01:03:28,214 --> 01:03:31,214
is to study the properties of Higgs bosons

1550
01:03:31,214 --> 01:03:33,214
and see if we can detect evidence

1551
01:03:33,214 --> 01:03:35,214
for these coupling constants.

1552
01:03:35,214 --> 01:03:37,214
So basically all the coupling constants,

1553
01:03:37,214 --> 01:03:39,214
regardless of where they come in,

1554
01:03:39,214 --> 01:03:41,214
are really probability numbers?

1555
01:03:41,214 --> 01:03:43,214
They're square roots of probability.

1556
01:03:47,214 --> 01:03:49,214
Sometimes they're fourth roots of probabilities.

1557
01:03:49,214 --> 01:03:51,214
It depends on how many times you have to square.

1558
01:03:51,214 --> 01:03:53,214
But yeah, right.

1559
01:03:53,214 --> 01:03:55,214
They're related to probabilities.

1560
01:03:59,214 --> 01:04:01,214
So there's an assumption here

1561
01:04:01,214 --> 01:04:03,214
that there's only one such Higgs boson

1562
01:04:03,214 --> 01:04:04,214
that everything couples?

1563
01:04:04,214 --> 01:04:06,214
I have made the assumption

1564
01:04:06,214 --> 01:04:08,214
that there's only one type of Higgs bosons.

1565
01:04:08,214 --> 01:04:10,214
In various more complicated theories

1566
01:04:10,214 --> 01:04:12,214
beyond the standard model,

1567
01:04:12,214 --> 01:04:14,214
there are often more than one.

1568
01:04:14,214 --> 01:04:16,214
And then much of what I have to say,

1569
01:04:16,214 --> 01:04:18,214
for example, there are Higgs bosons,

1570
01:04:18,214 --> 01:04:20,214
well, yeah, there are supersymmetric models,

1571
01:04:20,214 --> 01:04:22,214
there are usually two Higgs bosons,

1572
01:04:22,214 --> 01:04:25,214
but then you just modify it accordingly.

1573
01:04:25,214 --> 01:04:27,214
And of course much of what I say

1574
01:04:27,214 --> 01:04:29,214
has to be modified

1575
01:04:29,214 --> 01:04:32,214
because the weak interactions are SU2, not U1.

1576
01:04:32,214 --> 01:04:34,214
So what I'm doing is

1577
01:04:34,214 --> 01:04:36,214
giving you a kind of simplified version

1578
01:04:36,214 --> 01:04:38,214
of what the Higgs phenomena does.

1579
01:04:38,214 --> 01:04:42,214
But thus far, taking into account

1580
01:04:42,214 --> 01:04:46,214
all of the various gauge interactions,

1581
01:04:46,214 --> 01:04:48,214
here's an interesting fact.

1582
01:04:48,214 --> 01:04:52,214
All of the particles that are seen

1583
01:04:52,214 --> 01:04:54,214
in the standard model

1584
01:04:54,214 --> 01:04:56,214
could not have a mass

1585
01:04:56,214 --> 01:04:58,214
if it were not for this shift,

1586
01:04:58,214 --> 01:05:01,214
for this shift of the Higgs field.

1587
01:05:01,214 --> 01:05:03,214
The gauge bosons,

1588
01:05:03,214 --> 01:05:07,214
they normally do not have mass.

1589
01:05:07,214 --> 01:05:09,214
And the only way to give them the mass,

1590
01:05:09,214 --> 01:05:11,214
the only known way to give them mass,

1591
01:05:11,214 --> 01:05:14,214
is this phenomenon of spontaneous symmetry breaking

1592
01:05:14,214 --> 01:05:16,214
associated with the Higgs field.

1593
01:05:16,214 --> 01:05:18,214
Their mass is typically proportional

1594
01:05:18,214 --> 01:05:20,214
just to this F.

1595
01:05:20,214 --> 01:05:22,214
So the Z and W boson.

1596
01:05:22,214 --> 01:05:24,214
All of the fermions,

1597
01:05:24,214 --> 01:05:26,214
because of this peculiar property

1598
01:05:26,214 --> 01:05:31,214
that the weak interactions are purely left-handed,

1599
01:05:31,214 --> 01:05:33,214
the symmetries,

1600
01:05:33,214 --> 01:05:35,214
of the gauge theories,

1601
01:05:35,214 --> 01:05:37,214
do not allow you to just write down,

1602
01:05:37,214 --> 01:05:39,214
in other words, to postulate

1603
01:05:39,214 --> 01:05:42,214
a mathematical mass term for these fermions.

1604
01:05:42,214 --> 01:05:44,214
The only way that they get mass

1605
01:05:44,214 --> 01:05:47,214
is through this shift of the field.

1606
01:05:47,214 --> 01:05:49,214
To say it yet another way,

1607
01:05:49,214 --> 01:05:51,214
all of the masses of the known particles

1608
01:05:51,214 --> 01:05:54,214
are such that they are proportional

1609
01:05:54,214 --> 01:05:58,214
to this symmetry breaking parameter, F,

1610
01:05:58,214 --> 01:06:01,214
the shift of the Higgs field.

1611
01:06:01,214 --> 01:06:03,214
That's a curiosity which may be deep,

1612
01:06:03,214 --> 01:06:05,214
but may be important.

1613
01:06:05,214 --> 01:06:07,214
Question, if you have antiparticles

1614
01:06:07,214 --> 01:06:09,214
and they decay,

1615
01:06:09,214 --> 01:06:11,214
would the direction be the opposite?

1616
01:06:11,214 --> 01:06:14,214
Yes. That's a good point.

1617
01:06:14,214 --> 01:06:18,214
If an electron is purely left-handed,

1618
01:06:18,214 --> 01:06:21,214
then its antiparticle is purely right-handed.

1619
01:06:21,214 --> 01:06:24,214
But nevertheless, we continue to call it left-handed.

1620
01:06:24,214 --> 01:06:26,214
We call it...

1621
01:06:26,214 --> 01:06:29,214
We still say the electron is left-handed.

1622
01:06:29,214 --> 01:06:31,214
You say left-handed,

1623
01:06:31,214 --> 01:06:34,214
but is it left-handed anti-electron

1624
01:06:34,214 --> 01:06:37,214
or positron?

1625
01:06:37,214 --> 01:06:39,214
The positron would be right-handed.

1626
01:06:39,214 --> 01:06:42,214
The positron which interacts with the Z and W bosons

1627
01:06:42,214 --> 01:06:44,214
is right-handed.

1628
01:06:44,214 --> 01:06:46,214
So you'd call it biotent?

1629
01:06:46,214 --> 01:06:48,214
You'd call it biotent.

1630
01:06:48,214 --> 01:06:49,214
Biotent is not right-handed,

1631
01:06:49,214 --> 01:06:51,214
so it's antiparticle.

1632
01:06:51,214 --> 01:06:54,214
Uh, it's just a pure convention.

1633
01:06:54,214 --> 01:06:57,214
We have a lot more experience with electrons

1634
01:06:57,214 --> 01:06:59,214
than we do with positrons,

1635
01:06:59,214 --> 01:07:01,214
so we tend to name things

1636
01:07:01,214 --> 01:07:04,214
by the way we tend to say the electron,

1637
01:07:04,214 --> 01:07:06,214
meaning the full complex of objects

1638
01:07:06,214 --> 01:07:08,214
that go together with the electron

1639
01:07:08,214 --> 01:07:10,214
are called left-handed.

1640
01:07:10,214 --> 01:07:13,214
Nevertheless, the positron is right-handed.

1641
01:07:13,214 --> 01:07:16,214
So what do you do about the electrons and positrons?

1642
01:07:16,214 --> 01:07:19,214
What do you do about their...

1643
01:07:19,214 --> 01:07:21,214
Well, an electron and a positron,

1644
01:07:21,214 --> 01:07:22,214
if collided together,

1645
01:07:22,214 --> 01:07:25,214
can make, for example, a Z boson.

1646
01:07:25,214 --> 01:07:28,214
So I guess it would be a left-handed electron

1647
01:07:28,214 --> 01:07:31,214
and a right-handed positron,

1648
01:07:31,214 --> 01:07:34,214
could make a Z boson.

1649
01:07:34,214 --> 01:07:36,214
Right.

1650
01:07:36,214 --> 01:07:37,214
Okay.

1651
01:07:37,214 --> 01:07:41,214
Are all positrons created by the same thing?

1652
01:07:41,214 --> 01:07:42,214
No.

1653
01:07:42,214 --> 01:07:43,214
No, no, you can create positrons

1654
01:07:43,214 --> 01:07:45,214
in all kinds of ways.

1655
01:07:45,214 --> 01:07:49,214
Uh, you hit any particle hard enough with anything,

1656
01:07:49,214 --> 01:07:52,214
and it will make, among other things, positrons.

1657
01:07:52,214 --> 01:07:54,214
Right.

1658
01:07:54,214 --> 01:07:58,214
Certainly not all positrons in nature are made of, uh...

1659
01:07:58,214 --> 01:08:01,214
For example, you can make positrons, uh,

1660
01:08:01,214 --> 01:08:06,214
by just colliding an electron with a photon.

1661
01:08:06,214 --> 01:08:08,214
You hit an electron hard enough with a photon,

1662
01:08:08,214 --> 01:08:09,214
and you'll make...

1663
01:08:09,214 --> 01:08:10,214
The electron won't disappear,

1664
01:08:10,214 --> 01:08:16,214
but out will come an extra electron and a positron.

1665
01:08:16,214 --> 01:08:18,214
Okay, for example, let's see if we can work out

1666
01:08:18,214 --> 01:08:22,214
the Feynman diagram that describes that.

1667
